			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/17/business/Bank/Bank-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/17/business/Bank/Bank-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/17/business/Bank/Bank-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003005090" width="592" height="395" alt="Legal costs associated with the bankâs mortgage problems were partly responsible for a 43 percent drop in quarterly profit."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Legal costs associated with the bankâs mortgage problems were partly responsible for a 43 percent drop in quarterly profit.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Spencer Platt/Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/16/bank-of-america-earnings-slump-43/" data-title="Bank of America&#8217;s Settlement Negotiations Hit a Snag" data-description="Conflict over the liability of Bank of Americaâs Countrywide Financial and Merrill Lynch units have stalled the talks. The bank also reported a 43 percent drop in quarterly profit.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="entry entry-related">
<h4>Related Links</h4>
<div class="entry-related">
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.businesswire.com/news/home/20140716005547/en/Bank-America-Reports-Second-quarter-2014-Net-Income#.U8ZfLPldV8E">The earnings release</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/06/10/business/dealbook/11bank-timelime.html"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/multimedia/icons/interactive_icon.gif" alt="Interactive" width="9" height="9" border="0"> Timeline: Bank of America and the Financial Crisis</a></li>
</ul></div>
</p></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Once again, <a class="tickerized" title="More information about Bank of America Corporation" href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=BAC&amp;inline=nyt-org">Bank of America</a>âs troubled past is clouding its present and future.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After months of negotiations, a possible settlement with the Justice Department is in jeopardy over a disagreement on the bankâs liability for the suspected mortgage misdeeds of its <a class="tickerized" title="More articles about Countrywide Financial Corporation." href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/countrywide_financial_corporation/index.html?inline=nyt-org">Countrywide Financial</a> and <a class="tickerized" title="More articles about Merrill Lynch &amp; Co." href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/merrill_lynch_and_company/index.html?inline=nyt-org">Merrill Lynch</a> units, people briefed on the matter said. On Tuesday, the bankâs lawyers met in Washington with prosecutors from the Justice Department, but the two sides remain far from reaching a deal that could avert a lawsuit, these people said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And legal costs also dominated the bankâs second-quarter results Wednesday, dragging down its profits from a year ago and overshadowing the progress in its turnaround efforts.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A major sticking point in the talks with the Justice Department is how much the bank should be penalized for mortgage securities sold by Countrywide, which exists as a separate legal entity from Bank of America, one of the people said. Also, the bank has argued that in devising a penalty, prosecutors should take into account that Bank of America tried to back out of its purchase of Merrill, but felt pressured by regulators to go through with the acquisition in the depths of the financial crisis. Bank officials have argued in their talks with the Justice Department that they have already agreed to pay tens of billions of dollars to settle numerous lawsuits by investors and regulators related to mortgage abuses by Countrywide and that they are willing to pay billions more. But, they have said, the departmentâs demands are unfairly punitive.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Federal prosecutors left the meeting on Tuesday planning to move ahead with a lawsuit against Bank of America, another of the people said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The tensions appeared to spill out publicly on Wednesday in a speech in Washington to lawyers and trade groups by Tony West, the Justice Departmentâs lead negotiator in the case.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIf an institution is unwilling to admit its wrongful conduct in a statement of facts, or balks at paying a substantial penalty that reflects that conduct or refuses to do right by those affected, then we will not shrink from litigating,â Mr. West said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The No. 3 official at the department, Mr. West took another apparent dig at Bank of America and its recent offer to have its chief executive, <a class="tickerized" title="More articles about Brian T. Moynihan." href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/m/brian_t_moynihan/index.html?inline=nyt-per">Brian T. Moynihan</a>, meet with Attorney General <a class="tickerized" title="More articles about Eric H. Jr. Holder." href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/h/eric_h_holder_jr/index.html?inline=nyt-per">Eric H. Holder Jr.</a> to discuss settlement terms. The Justice Department rebuffed the request.<br />
		<div class="w190 right">
		<img src="//markets.on.nytimes.com/research/tools/builder/api.asp" width="190" height="250" alt=""/>		</div>
		<br />
âResolving these cases will require more than simply seeking a meeting with the attorney general,â Mr. West said. âIt will require taking true responsibility for misconduct that contributed to the Great Recession.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The two sides are also far apart on money. The Justice Department had been seeking as much as $17 billion, which would include a combination of a cash penalty and so-called soft-dollar relief for consumers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bank is offering roughly $12 billion â including about $3 billion in a cash penalty directly to the Treasury, the people said, with the rest earmarked for consumer relief measures.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This weekâs talks, which had been delayed while the government negotiated with <a class="tickerized" title="More information about Citigroup Inc" href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=C&amp;inline=nyt-org">Citigroup</a>, come after that bank agreed to a record $7 billion settlement with the Justice Department on Monday. Bank of America â along with its Countrywide Financial and Merrill Lynch units â was a relatively big player in the mortgage securities market.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In its second-quarter results, Bank of America reported profit of $2.3 billion, dragged down 43 percent from a year ago partly by $4 billion in legal expenses.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It was the second consecutive quarter that the bank reported a large legal expense. In the first quarter, the bank posted a quarterly loss as it reported legal costs of $6 billion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Wednesday, the bank also said it had reached a $650 million agreement with the <a class="tickerized" title="More information about American International Group Inc" href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=AIG&amp;inline=nyt-org">American International Group</a> in the quarter to settle mortgage securities litigation. When A.I.G. filed the lawsuit in 2011, the insurer was seeking to recover $10 billion in losses, one of the largest single mortgage securities claims ever filed by a single investor.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bank also said on Wednesday that A.I.G. had dropped its objection to an $8.5 billion settlement Bank of America reached with a group of 22 mortgage investors in a case known as the Article 77 proceedings. The deal removes a significant challenge to an agreement, which has been held up for more than two years.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Beyond the legal morass, Mr. Moynihan struck an optimistic tone on consumer spending and the bankâs ability to generate revenue in investment banking.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe economy continues to strengthen, and our customers and clients are doing more business with us,â Mr. Moynihan said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Global banking profits rose to $1.4 billion, from $1.3 billion a year ago, on strong equity underwriting fees, as trading revenue from fixed-income, currencies and commodities rose 5 percent.</p>
<div id="addendums" class="addendums"><div class="story-addendum theme-correction"><strong>Correction: July 16, 2014</strong> <br>An earlier version of this article misstated the value of assets in the bankâs global wealth and investment management business. It is $878 billion, not $878 million.</div></div><footer class="story-footer">
